         <abstract>
            <p>The problem of accounting for corporate combinations is a significant problem presently under review by the Accounting Principles Board of the American Institute of C.P.A.s Writings in recent years have been very critical of the pooling-of-interests method of accounting for these combinations. Therefore, the method may be disallowed unless action is taken in support of the pooling approach. Pooling, where done properly, is a much better way of accounting for combinations than the alternative "purchase" method, because the "pooled" financial statements can be meaningfully compared with prior year statements and with statements of other companies; whereas, under the purchase method, similar comparisons will lead to inappropriate conclusions.</p>
          </abstract>
